{
  "text": "Application of high-K ϩ saline to FM1-43-labeled synaptic boutons results in a second round of exocytosis that releases the dye contained within the SVs (unloading). Terminals loaded with FM1-43 for 5 min release most of this dye via the fast-cycling SV pool after a comparable 5 min unloading period (Fig. 4 A) . Under conditions of equal loading and unloading periods, the majority of dye in both wild-type (85.5 Ϯ 1.0%) and stn C (83.7 Ϯ 5.3%) NMJ synapses is released via Ca 2ϩ -dependent exocytosis (Fig.  4 A) . In contrast, shortening unloading times to 1 min of high-K ϩ saline application was still sufficient to unload the majority of dye in wild-type terminals (88.1 Ϯ 1.8%), but the amount of dye released from stoned boutons is significantly reduced (71.8 Ϯ 3.4%; p ϭ 0.0006; Fig. 4 B) . These findings confirm that the readily releasable pool is smaller in stoned mutants, and although these vesicles are competent to fuse, they do so in a slower time course. The impairment of dye release is consistent with the defect in exocytosis observed in stoned mutants [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and may result from the aberrant vesicle trafficking observed in stoned terminals. These data further suggest that the aberrantly distributed SVs in stn C mutants are releasable and do not have the \"barrier\" thought to spatially separate the reserve and ready SV pools [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "16456343",
